          "input": {
            "content": "# v0.6: LAN Relay — Design Spec\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Milestone:** v0.6 — LAN Relay\n**Status:** Design\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nRoute messages through LAN peers during partial Internet outages. A node in Personal Relay mode accepts envelopes from peers, stores them in a relay outbox, and delivers via the full tiered system (Direct, Quorum, BestEffort) — not just forward-to-Quorum.\n\nKey insight: the relay queue is an \"outbox without crypto.\" It reuses the same TransportCoordinator, delivery state machine, and retry logic as the client outbox. The only difference: no `inner_bytes`, no re-encryption, no DAG tracking — just opaque `envelope_bytes` → tiered delivery.\n\n---\n\n## Design decisions\n\n| Decision | Outcome | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Relay outbox structure | Generalize `ClientOutbox` with `OutboxOwnership` | Less duplication than a separate RelayOutbox; delivery state machine is identical |\n| Shared delivery logic | Extract into `reme-relay` crate | Node and client both need TransportCoordinator + outbox tick + peer policy |\n| Node operating modes | Both Infrastructure + Personal Relay in v0.6 | Config toggle; different deployments need different behavior |\n| TrustLevel prerequisite | Yes, build first | Relay policy needs trust levels to make capability decisions |\n| Security hardening prerequisite | Yes (#102, #116) | Relay trusts discovery results; discovery must be hardened first |\n| Peer policy | Configurable trust thresholds, not hardcoded | Network benefits from open relay; privacy-conscious users restrict it |\n| Relay delivery | Full tiered (Direct + Quorum + BestEffort) | Relay node might discover the actual recipient on LAN |\n| Fine-grained relay routing | Deferred | \"Relay only to node X\", \"no direct for relayed\" — additive, not needed for v0.6 |\n| BLE tier assignment | Contextual: Direct, relay, or BestEffort | No \"BLE mesh protocol\" — BLE relay is the same model as LAN HTTP relay |\n| ack_secret KDF change | Deferred to v0.7 | Needed for re-encryption (FLAG_DETACHED); v0.6 doesn't re-encrypt |\n\n---\n\n## Crate extraction: `reme-relay`\n\n### Motivation\n\nPersonal Relay nodes need TransportCoordinator + outbox tick + peer policy — all currently in client-only code. Extracting a shared crate avoids duplication and keeps delivery logic in one place.\n\n### What moves where\n\n| Current location | What | Destination |\n|---|---|---|\n| `reme-core` Client | `process_urgent_retries()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `process_maintenance()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `tiered_outbox_tick()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `tiered_config` field | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| New | `PeerPolicy` / `RelayPolicy` | `reme-relay` |\n| New | `OutboxOwnership` enum | `reme-outbox` |\n| `reme-core` Client | `prepare_message()`, crypto, DAG, tombstones | Stays in `reme-core` |\n\n### Proposed crate graph\n\n```\nreme-relay (NEW — shared delivery engine)\n├── reme-transport (TransportCoordinator, targets, delivery config)\n├── reme-outbox (generalized: Own vs Relay entries)\n├── reme-discovery (mDNS, peer verification)\n└── reme-storage (Contact with TrustLevel — for policy lookups)\n\nreme-core (Client API — crypto + user-facing logic)\n├── reme-relay (delivery engine)\n├── reme-encryption (encrypt/decrypt)\n├── reme-message (wire formats)\n└── Client-specific: prepare_message(), send_text_tiered(), DAG tracking,\n    tombstone handling, message decryption\n\nreme-node-core (Node API — mailbox + relay)\n├── reme-relay (delivery engine) ← NEW dependency\n├── reme-storage (MailboxStore)\n├── reme-message\n└── Node-specific: mailbox storage, operating mode toggle,\n    HTTP API handlers, gossip replication (Infrastructure mode)\n```\n\n### DeliveryEngine\n\n```rust\n/// Shared delivery engine used by both Client and Node (Personal Relay mode).\n/// Drives the outbox tick loop: urgent retries, maintenance refreshes, expiry.\npub struct DeliveryEngine<S: OutboxStorage> {\n    coordinator: Arc<TransportCoordinator>,\n    outbox: ClientOutbox<S>,\n    config: TieredDeliveryConfig,\n}\n\nimpl<S: OutboxStorage> DeliveryEngine<S> {\n    /// Combined tick: expire messages, process urgent retries, run maintenance.\n    pub async fn tick(&self) -> Result<TickResult, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Process urgent retries for messages that haven't reached quorum.\n    pub async fn process_urgent_retries(&self) -> Result<Vec<RetryResult>, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Process maintenance refreshes for distributed messages.\n    pub async fn process_maintenance(&self) -> Result<usize, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Enqueue an envelope for relay delivery (no inner_bytes).\n    pub fn enqueue_relay(\n        &self,\n        routing_key: RoutingKey,\n        message_id: MessageID,\n        envelope_bytes: &[u8],\n        ttl_ms: Option<u64>,\n    ) -> Result<OutboxEntryId, DeliveryError>;\n}\n```\n\nThe Client wraps DeliveryEngine and adds crypto (`prepare_message()` → `engine.outbox.enqueue()` with `Ownership::Own`). The Node uses `engine.enqueue_relay()` directly.\n\n---\n\n## Contact model rework (#179)\n\n### TrustLevel enum\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, PartialOrd, Ord)]\n#[repr(u8)]\npub enum TrustLevel {\n    Stranger = 0,   // Auto-created from incoming message\n    Known = 1,      // Manually added, not verified\n    Verified = 2,   // Identity confirmed (LAN challenge-response, QR, out-of-band)\n    Trusted = 3,    // User-designated trusted contact\n}\n```\n\n`PartialOrd`/`Ord` derived so threshold comparisons work naturally: `peer.trust_level >= policy.relay_for`.\n\n### Contact struct (moved to reme-storage or shared types)\n\n```rust\npub struct Contact {\n    pub id: i64,\n    pub public_id: PublicID,\n    pub routing_key: RoutingKey,      // derived from public_id, persisted for indexing\n    pub name: Option<String>,\n    pub trust_level: TrustLevel,\n    pub verified_at: Option<i64>,     // unix timestamp of last verification\n    pub created_at: i64,\n}\n```\n\n### Schema migration\n\n```sql\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN routing_key BLOB;\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN trust_level INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1;\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN verified_at INTEGER;\nCREATE INDEX idx_contacts_routing_key ON contacts(routing_key);\n```\n\nDefault `trust_level = 1` (Known) for existing contacts — they were manually added.\n\n### Integration points\n\n- `Client::add_contact()` — default `Known` for manual adds\n- Auto-created from incoming messages — `Stranger`\n- `DiscoveryController` verification success — upgrade to `Verified` + set `verified_at`\n- `Client::set_trust_level()` — user-initiated trust changes\n\n---\n\n## Peer capability policy\n\n### Three policy axes\n\n| Policy | Controls | Question it answers |\n|---|---|---|\n| `accept_from` | HTTP POST /api/v1/submit | \"Who can push envelopes into my mailbox?\" |\n| `relay_for` | Relay queue → TransportCoordinator | \"Whose envelopes do I forward via my transports?\" |\n| `direct_deliver` | Discovery → Direct tier registration | \"Whose messages do I route to discovered LAN peers?\" |\n\n### Configuration\n\n```toml\n[relay.policy]\n# Trust level thresholds (\"any\", \"known+\", \"verified+\", \"trusted\", \"none\")\naccept_from = \"any\"           # default: accept from everyone\nrelay_for = \"verified+\"       # default: relay for verified and trusted contacts\ndirect_deliver = \"verified+\"  # default: direct deliver for verified and trusted\n\n# Per-trust-level rate limits (requests per minute, 0 = unlimited)\n[relay.rate_limits]\nstranger = 5\nknown = 30\nverified = 100\ntrusted = 0\n```\n\nThe `+` suffix means \"this level and above.\" `direct_deliver` replaces the current `auto_direct_known_contacts` boolean.\n\n### Default policy table\n\n| TrustLevel | accept_from=any | relay_for=verified+ | direct_deliver=verified+ |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Stranger | Yes (rate-limited 5/min) | No | No |\n| Known | Yes (rate-limited 30/min) | No | No |\n| Verified | Yes (100/min) | Yes | Yes |\n| Trusted | Yes (unlimited) | Yes | Yes |\n\n### RelayPolicy struct\n\n```rust\npub struct RelayPolicy {\n    pub accept_from: TrustThreshold,\n    pub relay_for: TrustThreshold,\n    pub direct_deliver: TrustThreshold,\n    pub rate_limits: PerTrustRateLimits,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]\npub enum TrustThreshold {\n    None,        // disabled\n    Any,         // all peers including strangers\n    KnownPlus,   // Known, Verified, Trusted\n    VerifiedPlus, // Verified, Trusted\n    TrustedOnly, // Trusted only\n}\n\nimpl TrustThreshold {\n    pub fn allows(&self, level: TrustLevel) -> bool {\n        match self {\n            Self::None => false,\n            Self::Any => true,\n            Self::KnownPlus => level >= TrustLevel::Known,\n            Self::VerifiedPlus => level >= TrustLevel::Verified,\n            Self::TrustedOnly => level >= TrustLevel::Trusted,\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Node operating modes (#23)\n\n### Configuration\n\n```toml\n[node]\nmode = \"infrastructure\"  # \"infrastructure\" or \"personal_relay\"\n\n[node.personal_relay]\nquorum = { count = 2 }\noutbox_enabled = true\nurgent_initial_delay_secs = 5\nurgent_max_delay_secs = 300\nmaintenance_interval_hours = 4\n```\n\n### Behavior differences\n\n| Aspect | Infrastructure | Personal Relay |\n|---|---|---|\n| Inbound envelopes | Store in mailbox | Store in mailbox + enqueue in relay outbox |\n| Outbound delivery | Fire-and-forget gossip (`ReplicationClient`) | Tiered delivery via `DeliveryEngine` |\n| Persistence | Mailbox only | Mailbox + relay outbox |\n| Retry logic | None | Full 3-phase (urgent → distributed → confirmed) |\n| Discovery | Optional (mDNS for node-to-node) | Recommended (enables Direct tier relay) |\n| Use case | Public mailbox serving many users | Home server, personal relay, gateway |\n\n### Implementation\n\n```rust\nenum NodeMode {\n    Infrastructure {\n        replication: ReplicationClient,\n    },\n    PersonalRelay {\n        engine: DeliveryEngine<SqliteOutboxStorage>,\n        policy: RelayPolicy,\n    },\n}\n```\n\nOn envelope receipt:\n- **Infrastructure**: `mailbox.store()` + `replication.broadcast()` (fire-and-forget)\n- **Personal Relay**: `mailbox.store()` + `engine.enqueue_relay()` (persistent, tiered)\n\n---\n\n## Outbox generalization\n\n### OutboxOwnership\n\n```rust\npub enum OutboxOwnership {\n    /// Our own message — has inner_bytes for potential re-encryption (v1.0)\n    Own,\n    /// Relaying for someone else — opaque envelope only\n    Relay,\n}\n```\n\n### Schema change\n\n```sql\nALTER TABLE outbox_entries ADD COLUMN ownership INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;\n-- 0 = Own, 1 = Relay\n```\n\n`inner_bytes` becomes optional — Relay entries store empty bytes. The delivery state machine (urgent → distributed → confirmed) is identical for both.\n\n### Relay-specific behavior\n\n- **No DAG tracking**: Relay entries don't update sender DAG state\n- **No re-encryption**: `inner_bytes` is empty; can't re-encrypt for different transport\n- **TTL from envelope**: Relay entries respect the OuterEnvelope's `ttl_hours` field\n- **Confirmation**: Relay entries transition to Confirmed when quorum is reached (no tombstone — relay node won't receive tombstones for others' messages)\n\n---\n\n## Relay flow (Personal Relay mode)\n\n```\nPeer submits envelope via HTTP POST /api/v1/submit\n    │\n    ├─ Node stores in mailbox (existing behavior, for recipient to fetch)\n    │\n    └─ RelayPolicy.relay_for.allows(peer_trust_level)?\n        │\n        ├─ No → done (stored locally only, not relayed)\n        │\n        └─ Yes → DeliveryEngine.enqueue_relay(routing_key, message_id, envelope_bytes)\n            │\n            └─ Outbox tick loop:\n                ├─ Tier 1 Direct: recipient discovered on LAN? → deliver directly\n                ├─ Tier 2 Quorum: forward to configured HTTP mailboxes / MQTT\n                └─ Tier 3 BestEffort: fire-and-forget to LoRa/Meshtastic if available\n```\n\n---\n\n## Security hardening prerequisites\n\n### #102: Enforce public_id on direct peers\n\nScope Tier 1 routing so that direct delivery only targets peers whose `public_id` matches the message's `routing_key`. Currently, a discovered peer could theoretically receive envelopes not addressed to them. The fix: `TransportCoordinator` checks `target.config().can_serve(&envelope.routing_key)` — already partially implemented, needs enforcement.\n\n### #116: Channel binding for identity challenge-response\n\nThe current LAN identity verification (`GET /api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>`) proves that the peer controls the claimed identity key, but doesn't bind the proof to the transport channel (HTTP connection). An attacker on the same LAN could MITM the verification. Fix: include transport-layer binding (e.g., TLS session ID or ephemeral connection nonce) in the signed challenge response.\n\n---\n\n## Dependency graph\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n    subgraph \"Layer 0: Prerequisites\"\n        A179[\"#179 TrustLevel + Contact rework\"]\n        A102[\"#102 public_id enforcement\"]\n        A116[\"#116 channel binding\"]\n        A145[\"#145 node mDNS discovery\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 1: Foundation\"\n        B1[\"reme-relay crate extraction\"]\n        B2[\"Outbox generalization (Own vs Relay)\"]\n        B75[\"#75 Peer capability policy\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 2: Relay\"\n        C23[\"#23 Node operating modes\"]\n        C2[\"Relay queue ingress\"]\n        C3[\"Relay queue egress (tiered)\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 3: Integration\"\n        D1[\"Integration tests\"]\n        D2[\"Documentation\"]\n    end\n\n    A179 --> B75\n    A102 --> B1\n    A116 --> B1\n    A145 --> C23\n    B1 --> C23\n    B2 --> C2\n    B75 --> C2\n    B75 --> C3\n    C23 --> C2\n    C23 --> C3\n    C2 --> D1\n    C3 --> D1\n    D1 --> D2\n```\n\n---\n\n## Deferred from v0.6\n\n- **ack_secret deterministic KDF** — needed for re-encryption in v0.7, not for v0.6 relay\n- **FLAG_DETACHED re-encryption** — v0.7 when BLE arrives\n- **Fine-grained relay routing** — \"relay only to node X\", \"no direct for relayed messages\"\n- **Relay-specific rate limiting at transport level** — per-target, not just per-trust-level\n- **BLE transport** — v0.7\n- **LoRa/Meshtastic transport** — v0.8\n\n---\n\n## Success criteria\n\n- Alice (no Internet) sends to Charlie (external) via Bob (has Internet + relay mode)\n- Message delivered when Bob's relay queue processes it through tiered delivery\n- Bob can also discover Charlie on LAN and deliver directly (if Charlie is local)\n- Relay path visible in delivery status\n- Policy prevents Stranger peers from relaying through the node (default config)\n- Works transparently with existing client outbox retry logic\n- Node operating mode toggle works (Infrastructure vs Personal Relay)\n- Integration tests cover relay round-trip with trust level checks\n",
