          "input": {
            "file_path": "/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/WHITEPAPER.md",
            "new_string": "v0.6 ships with HTTP-only ingress and Quorum egress (no Direct-tier relay from nodes — nodes do not perform active peer discovery). v0.9 adds Meshtastic ingress (BLE uses the same relay model as LAN HTTP, no special adapter). v0.10 adds Meshtastic egress and BLE relay to discovered peers.\n\n**Trust model:** Relay nodes see routing keys, message sizes, and coarse timestamps. E2E encryption prevents relay nodes from reading or forging message content, but it does **not** eliminate metadata leakage or availability abuse. Anonymous discovered relays are therefore not equivalent to configured trusted peers: they are suitable for constrained best-effort relay roles, while exact-key fetch, quorum credit, and replication remain trusted-peer functions.\n\n**Trust-based relay policy (v0.6+):** Relay decisions are governed by configurable trust thresholds. Each contact has a `TrustLevel` (Stranger, Known, Verified, Trusted) defined in the `reme-contact` crate. Two policy axes control relay behavior: `accept_from` (who can submit envelopes) and `relay_for` (whose envelopes the node forwards). Default: strangers can submit but not relay. See §11.6 for identity verification that feeds trust state.\n\n**Relay state machine:** Relay entries use a simplified 2-phase delivery model: Urgent (aggressive retry until quorum) → Relayed (handoff complete, cleanup after delay). The `Relayed` terminal state is distinct from `Confirmed` (which means recipient acknowledged via DAG/tombstone). Relay entries also carry a `source_target` to prevent echo loops — the originating peer is excluded from egress.",
