ge identity.\n\n3. **Per-chunk integrity verification:** The three-layer integrity chain (chunk hash -> transfer hash -> VSF hash) is overkill for reme's HTTP-based transport (TLS provides integrity), but would be relevant if reme adds UDP or BLE transports where corruption is possible.\n\n**What NOT to adopt:** The Blast-256 congestion control is inappropriate for reme. It is designed for dedicated peer-to-peer links and would be hostile on shared internet paths. If reme ever adds UDP transport, standard CUBIC or BBR congestion control would be more appropriate.\n\n### 4. LAN Discovery Approach\n\n**Photon** (`NETWORK.md` lines 64-96, `status.rs` line 142-148):\n- Raw UDP broadcast to `255.255.255.255:4383` with a VSF packet containing `handle_proof` and `port`.\n- Very simple: broadcast IP, parse responses, match by handle_proof.\n- No service type abstraction, no DNS-SD, no multicast.\n- NAT hairpinning: FGTW bootstrap includes `local_ip` field so peers behind the same public IP can use LAN addresses instead.\n- LAN discovery is a single request type (`pt_disc`) discriminated at the packet level.\n\n**reme** (`crates/reme-discovery/`):\n- Proper mDNS-SD using the `mdns_sd` crate, browsing `_reme._tcp.local.`.\n- `DiscoveryBackend` trait (in `backend.rs`) abstracts over discovery mechanisms (mDNS, future BLE).\n- `AdvertisementSpec` includes routing key, port, TXT records, and service type.\n- Privacy-preserving instance names derived from routing key (noted in `types.rs` line 48-49).\n- Structured event system: `PeerDiscovered`, `PeerUpdated`, `PeerLost` events via broadcast channels.\n- Full verification flow: discovered peers are verified via HTTP challenge-response before being registered as ephemeral targets.\n\n**Assessment:** reme's approach is strictly superior:\n- mDNS multicast is more reliable than raw broadcast (works across VLANs with mDNS relay, respects network topology).\n- DNS-SD provides structured metadata via TXT records.\n- Privacy-preserving 