y, contact names, keys).\n\n2. **`Zeroize`/`ZeroizeOnDrop` audit.** Photon's `Seed` type derives `Zeroize` + `ZeroizeOnDrop` for secret material. reme should audit that MIK private keys and ECDH shared secrets in `reme-identity` and `reme-encryption` are zeroized on drop.\n\n3. **Hybrid X25519 + ML-KEM-768 for post-quantum resistance (V2).** Photon's 8-algorithm CLUTCH ceremony (550KB payload, includes McEliece) is overkill and hostile to constrained transports. But the threat is real. A single hybrid KEM (X25519 + ML-KEM-768, ~1.1KB overhead) is the industry-standard approach used by Signal's PQXDH and Chrome. Negotiate via version flag in OuterEnvelope.\n\n#### Medium priority\n\n4. **TrustLevel enum for contacts.** Photon's `Stranger → Known → Trusted → Inner` graduated trust model is a good template for when reme adds contact verification flows.\n\n5. **Sync records during peer verification.** Photon's pong messages include per-conversation \"last received time\" so peers can efficiently retransmit only what was missed. reme achieves this through DAG `observed_heads`, but a lightweight sync exchange during mDNS peer refresh could reduce unnecessary retransmission in Phase 2 maintenance.\n\n6. **WritePolicy distinction.** Photon's `MustSucceed` (with read-back verification + fsync) vs `BestEffort` for persistence is elegant. Crypto chain state gets paranoid writes; avatars get best-effort. reme could adopt this for outbox state vs display preferences.\n\n#### Low priority / future reference\n\n7. **Optional `prev_content_hash` in InnerEnvelope** for opportunistic forward secrecy when both peers happen to be online — mix the hash of the last received message into ephemeral key derivation. Purely advisory (messages remain independently decryptable without it).\n\n8. **Zero-metadata-leakage filenames** for any future file-based storage (attachments, bundle exports) — derive opaque filenames from keyed hashes instead of using plaintext names.\n\n9. **Tick-driven fall