          "text": "OK, now I have the full picture. Let me think through this properly.\n\nYou're right — there are two distinct problems:\n\n**1. Identity oracle (your main concern).** The `/api/v1/identity` endpoint will sign any challenge for anyone who asks. An attacker who knows (or guesses) a set of PublicIDs can send challenges to every IP on the LAN, try verifying the signature against each candidate PublicID, and build a map of `IP → PublicID`. The response doesn't return the public key (good), but brute-forcing against a small candidate set is trivial. Even without mDNS routing key broadcast, the identity endpoint is an oracle.\n\n**2. One-directional verification.** Only the challenger verifies the responder. The responder never learns who's asking or why — it just signs whatever comes in. This means:\n- Passive enumeration by strangers\n- No basis for the responder to apply access control (e.g., \"only respond if the challenger is a known contact\")\n\n**The fix: mutual authentication.** The challenger should prove they know who they're looking for (or prove their own identity) before the responder reveals anything. A few options:\n\n| Approach | How it works | Trade-off |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Challenger commits to target** | Challenge includes `BLAKE3(challenger_pubkey \\|\\| target_routing_key)`. Responder only signs if the commitment matches their own routing key. | Prevents blind enumeration. Attacker must already know the routing key to get a response. Pairs well with future non-broadcast mDNS. |\n| **Mutual challenge-response** | Two-round protocol: challenger sends `(their_pubkey, challenge_a)`, responder replies `(signature_b, challenge_b)`, challenger replies `(signature_a)`. Both sides verify. | Strongest — both parties authenticated. Extra round trip. |\n| **ECDH-gated response** | Challenger sends an ephemeral X25519 pubkey + encrypted target routing key. Responder decrypts with their MIK, checks if routing key matches, only then signs. | Prev