─────────────────────────────┤\n│  Session Envelope (LAN/Tor — Tier 1)               │\n│  Noise XX session, drop sig + from                  │\n│  ~148B overhead, forward secrecy                    │\n│  Requires completed handshake                       │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Compact Frame (LoRa/BLE — Tier 3)                 │\n│  session_tag + counter + AEAD                       │\n│  12-22B overhead, session-only                      │\n│  Requires active session, no DAG, ephemeral         │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\nThe same message can be sent as a Full Envelope to the mailbox AND as a Compact Frame over LoRa simultaneously — the outbox just picks the right format per target. The content is identical; only the framing changes.\n\n## Open questions\n\n1. **session_tag collision** — with 2B tag and ~10 active sessions, collision probability per incoming frame is ~10/65536 ≈ 0.015%. Acceptable? If not, 4B gives ~0.000001%.\n\n2. **Counter rollover** — u16 gives 65K messages per session direction. For LoRa (low throughput) this is years of use. Re-key on rollover.\n\n3. **Session bootstrap on LoRa** — how does the first session get established? Probably not over LoRa itself (too expensive). Bootstrap via LAN/HTTP, then use the session for LoRa. Or: pre-shared key via QR code contact exchange.\n\n4. **Relay forwarding** — if a LoRa mesh relay receives a Compact Frame, it can't read the routing_key (it's implicit in session_tag). Relays would need to broadcast blindly or maintain a forwarding table. This is a fundamental trade-off of the compact format.\n\nWant me to write this up as a spec draft?",
